docs.abstract: Tyler Perry revives his signature character — this time for Netflix — in a fast, nonsensical new Madea movie.
docs.snippet: Tyler Perry revives his signature character — this time for Netflix — in a fast, nonsensical new Madea movie.
docs.lead_paragraph: Midway through “Tyler Perry’s A Madea Homecoming,” there’s a gag that captures the humor of Perry’s multimedia Madea franchise. Perry halts the plot for a black-and-white flashback where his short-tempered, unfiltered titular matriarch tells the story of how she kick-started the Civil Rights movement by threatening her man’s mistress, Rosa Parks, who then took sanctuary on a Montgomery bus. As proof, Madea brandishes a photo she took in the moment on her smartphone. “My aPhone,” she says, “because they didn’t have iPhone back then — it was A before I.” It’s unapologetic, irreverent nonsense — but it should get a laugh, so why not? Perry, who claimed that he would retire his signature character after 2019’s “A Madea Family Funeral,” has resurrected Madea, it seems, in that same spirit: simply because he can.

headline.main: ‘Tyler Perry’s A Madea Homecoming’ Review: Tyler’s Hard Lemonade
headline.print_headline: This Matriarch Wants To Bust Your Chops

docs.abstract: They need a social movement powerful enough to force liberal elites to advance sweeping reforms, rather than tinker around the edges of a broken system.
docs.snippet: They need a social movement powerful enough to force liberal elites to advance sweeping reforms, rather than tinker around the edges of a broken system.
docs.lead_paragraph: Why have Joe Biden’s ambitions for a new New Deal stalled, if not completely run aground? The pitch for the president’s Build Back Better program on the White House website certainly sounds like something Franklin Roosevelt could have said during the Great Depression: It calls “the hard work and ingenuity of the American people” the greatest “economic engine” the world has ever seen, but charges that “for too long, the economy has worked great for those at the top, while working families continually get squeezed.”

headline.main: Democrats Used to Be Able to Get Things Done. What Happened?
headline.print_headline: What the Democrats Need to Do
